She turned to a blank page and noted the date. Below, she wrote "11/05/648 - 13/12/648."
"Are you reading old memories?", Ivory asked, looking at the old notebook. Kari nodded her head. "Do you think they'll let you out for Christmas? It's almost in a few days."
Kari tapped twice on the lantern. No. Ivory had seen right. The Ice King never let Kari out, because she was "an error" in his eyes. She was born mute, and she was the only daughter of the family, which otherwise consisted only of boys.
Ivory was also, in her own way. When she had reported her non-binary status, it was as if the world had changed too. They had been given tasks that condemned her to solitude, as punishment for her difference.
She also had to stay in service to the princess, but that wasn't too bad, because it made her a friend.
"It's almost your birthday, I think?", asked Ivory, recalling that the princess's birthday was falling in a few days. Kari nodded her head, a sad spark in her pale blue eyes.
"Do you want to celebrate it?" While asking the question, she remembered what she had replied to him the last time.
No, Kari dismissed the subject. Ivory knew that it was a difficult topic for her. It was the day when she had been confined to her room and her mother had been banished. Ivory was still a baby when it happened, but she remembered the indignation of the servants and the inhabitants. She had heard that Queen Eirwen was a good queen, but that she also had this strange ability to predict the future.
"Well... what do you want to do?", she asked. Kari looked up with enthusiasm. She offered Ivory a piece of paper. But when she glanced at it...
Painting cloth 15 cm x 15 cm
Blanc, several nuances of blue paint
6 brushes of different sizes
Easel
"You want me to find those things for you?", said Ivory as she turned to the silent princess who was typing frantically, shaking her curls from front to back. "Yes?" She giggled slightly at seeing the usually reserved princess get passionate about something. It was the first time she asked for something unrelated to books and not found in her room.
"Alright. See you later?", proposed Ivory as she stood up and made her way through the pile of papers and notebooks.
Kari acquiesça and plunged back into her memories by wrapping herself back up in her thick quilt.
She left the room with relief. The princess was finally stepping out of her comfort zone by asking for things that weren't her concern, like paint.
She retraced her steps through the corridors, trying not to listen to the whispers of the servants.
"I've heard she's possessed by Queen Eirwen, that's why she always goes into that room."
"I've heard she eats children in that room."
"She resembles a man, doesn't she?"
She covered her ears, because trying to ignore them didn't work. She headed towards the royal painter's room, which was located east, second door to the left.
Ivory approached the door, which was also carved, just like Kari's. It featured a white dragon, one of the 6 primordial dragons, which according to legend had created Frostfell. It was normal for the painter to expose it on his door. He liked the story.
She opened the door, expecting to find a normal scene. Paint stains everywhere, scattered pencils and papers in the room, easels covering every inch of the wall. Surprisingly, she saw none of that. The room was clean and there was a red velvet backdrop with a stool right in front. On the stool, the prince Aquilo was sitting, having his portrait painted.
"Ah, good day, Ivory! You came to watch your future king pose for a portrait?", Aquilo asked Ivory, throwing her a wink.
"Pardon, little prince", she replied, ignoring him partially, to search for the objects that her silent friend wanted. "I'm just here to retrieve supplies".
"Ah, will the little girl be leaving very soon?", Aquilo asked, "But I wanted to see you!"
"Well, not me". Ivory found the art supplies from her list and had placed them in a box she had found. "And I'm not a girl."
The prince hadn't thought about that, however. "Oh my dear, you know well that it's just a phase! It will pass when you grow up!", he muttered.
"I must be going", she said, suddenly feeling uneasy, due to the prince's words, which reminded her of all the bad things people said about her gender identity. I really want to get away from him.
"You're leaving us already?" The Prince appeared at the door immediately, ignoring the painter's complaints.
"That's not the behavior of a future king!" he scolded him.
"No one will know. The others won't believe you, and the painter won't say anything if he wants to stay alive." He turned back towards the painter for a second, then leaned in towards Ivory. "How about a gallant appointment?" He shuddered. Certainly, he had received many threats in the past, but never from a prince, especially one who was heir to the throne.
"Don't you know what the word 'no' means?" he launched at the Prince, pushing him out of the way.
"Not at all," replied Aquilo with a smile. Obviously, the prince who gets everything he wants doesn't know what this word means.
Ivory rolled his eyes. "Why would you want a romantic date with me rather than with others? You must have a good hundred pretenders?"
He interrupted him, still smiling all the time: "500, to be exact". He threw his hair back, making it fly through the cold air.
"So, why me rather than another? I am the threat to the palace." He wrapped his arms around his body.
"You are the most beautiful girl I have ever seen." Aquilo placed his finger under his chin and forced Ivory to look at him.
